\subsection{Threat and Stressors}
\label{subsec:threats}

Kelp forests are experiencing multiple interacting stressors that can lead to sudden state changes. \citet{Starko2024} offer the best assessment of BC kelp forest dynamics, which documents variable patterns of change along the province's coastline:

\textbf{Thermal stress:} Marine heatwaves, especially the 2014--2016 Blob'' event, led to massive mortality of kelp by direct physiological stress \citep{Bond2015, DiLorenzoMantua2016, Smale2019}. In the southern Salish Sea, summer sea surface temperatures regularly exceed the 18--20degC thresholds beyond which kelp photosynthesis and growth are impaired \citep{MoraSoto2024]. \citet{Berry2021] documented a 63% decline in bull kelp extent in South Puget Sound over 145 years, with losses concentrated along wave-sheltered shorelines with elevated temperatures. \citet{Schroeder2020] documented a 48.6% decline in kelp extent from 2015 to 20 The Kelpwatch platform developed by \citet{Bell2023} showed that 18.6% of regional sites in California and Mexico showed significant long-term trends, with variable recovery patterns following marine heatwaves. In northern California, \citet{RogersBennett2019} documented catastrophic losses (>90%) of bull kelp canopy following the marine heatwave, with persistent urchin barrens preventing recovery \citep{McPherson2021}. The time lag between thermal stress and population decline (around 1 year) makes it difficult to attribute but is consistent with effects on reproduction and juvenile survival.

\textbf{Trophic cascades:} Kelp declines despite cooler temperatures that should have favoured kelp growth occurred in northern BC. The reason is the 2013--2017 sea star wasting disease epidemic, which essentially wiped out the sunflower sea star (Pycnopodia helianthoides) across its range \citep{Hamilton2021, Harvell2019}. Sunflower stars were the main predator of urchins in many places; their removal caused explosive urchin population growth and subsequent overgrazing of kelp, a phenomenon called trophic cascade to urchin barrens'' \citep{Burt2018, EstesDuggins1995, Ling2015]. This trophic cascade mechanism has been described worldwide as a major cause of kelp forest collapse \citep{Ling2009, EstesPalmisano1974}.

\textbf{Wave exposure:} Physical disturbance from storm waves directly removes kelp biomass, but moderate wave action can also be beneficial to kelp by limiting urchin grazing (urchins are dislodged by wave surge) and increasing nutrient delivery through water mixing. The relationship between wave exposure and kelp persistence is therefore not linear and context-dependent \citep{Starko2024}.

\subsection{Resilience and Recovery}
\label{subsec:resilience}

Kelp forest resilience differs greatly along the BC coastline, with different mechanisms providing stability in different regions. \citet{MoraSoto2024} identified four environmental clusters in the southern Salish Sea, each with different patterns of resilience:

\begin{enumerate}
    \item \textbf{Cold, exposed sites} (e.g. outer coast of southern Vancouver Island): High resilience sustained by favourable thermal conditions buffering against the impacts of heatwave.

    \item \textbf{Semi-sheltered sites}: Moderate resilience, where there may be benefits from less wave stress with sufficient water mixing.

    \item \textbf{Strait of Georgia sites}: Lower resilience, with the highest temperatures and greatest variability of kelp persistence.

    \item \textbf{Warm, protected sites}: Overall low kelp abundance, but potentially exhibiting resilience where local conditions provide thermal refugia.
\end{enumerate}

At a provincial scale, \citet{Starko2024} found that areas with sea otter populations had increased stability, indicating the importance of top-down trophic control. Where sea otters were present, urchin grazing was suppressed irrespective of sunflower star status, providing functional redundancy in the predator guild.

\subsection{Phase Shifts and Tipping Points}
\label{subsec:phase-shifts}

The transition from kelp forest to urchin barren is a classic example of an ecological phase shift - a rapid reorganization of an ecosystem state that may be hard to reverse \citep{Holling1973, Steneck2002, Steneck2008, FilbeeDexter2018}. \citet{FilbeeDexter2014} reviewed sea urchin barrens as alternative stable states of collapsed kelp ecosystems in a comprehensive review, while \citet{Wilman2021} constructed a mathematical model of the predator-urchin-k Once urchins reach high densities, they can sustain a barren'' state even if conditions are otherwise favorable for recovery of kelp, producing hysteresis in the system dynamics \citep{Ling2015}. Despite regional collapse, some refugia remain where kelp survives despite unfavorable regional conditions \citep{CavanaughKC2023} and therefore the importance of fine-scale monitoring to identify and protect such areas.

Understanding and detecting such phase shifts is one of the key motivations of adaptive monitoring systems. Traditional monitoring approaches that assume gradual and linear change may not be able to capture the leading indicators of impending state shifts \citep{Reed2016} whereas adaptive systems that track regime-specific dynamics may be able to provide early warning of critical transitions. \citet{Reed2015} stressed the importance of broad temporal and spatial perspectives for understanding kelp forest dynamics, and demonstrated through the Santa Barbara Coastal LTER that short-term, small-scale studies often fail to capture the drivers of ecosystem change. Long-term monitoring datasets are crucial for understanding the variability of kelp forests over temporal scales \citep{Malone2022, Pfister2018} and \citet{Krumhansl2024} showed that kelp forests in Nova Scotia demonstrated resilience in the face of rapid ocean warming, with shifts in community composition in favour of warm-tolerant species, but a stability in overall kelp abundance.

\subsection{Geographic Variability & Implications for Monitoring}
\label{subsec:geographic-variability}

A critical challenge for kelp forest monitoring systems is the great geographic variability in kelp species, environmental conditions, and ecosystem dynamics in different coastal regions. This variability has profound implications for the design of detection algorithms, and suggests that adaptive, context-aware approaches may perform better than universal models.

\textbf{Scale-dependent processes:} \citet{Marzinelli2015} showed that processes that structure assemblages of kelp at small scales (10--100~m) do not generalize well to large scales (100--1,000~km), because of inherent spatial and temporal variability in natural systems. \citet{UnderwoodPetraitis1993} formalized this challenge, arguing that comparisons of local processes across different locations have to take explicit account of the role of scale in pattern detection. This basic ecological knowledge suggests that algorithms for monitoring optimized for one spatial or temporal scale may not work well at others.

\textbf{Regional kelp communities:} Different geographical regions host different assemblages of kelp species with different morphologies and spectral signatures. In the Arctic, \citet{Bischof2019} documented how \textit{Laminaria solidungula} and other kelp species in Kongsfjorden respond to unique Arctic stressors including UV radiation, ice cover dynamics and progressive Atlantification'' - conditions fundamentally different to temperate kelp forests. Australian temperate reefs are dominated by Ecklonia radiata, and the amount of kelp cover increases with latitude but is highly variable on smaller scales \citep{Marzinelli2015, ConnellIrving2008}. In the northeastern Atlantic, \citet{Voerman2013} documented climate driven changes in NW Spain kelp communities, including a decline of nearly 1400 ha and changes in species composition that favored warm tolerant taxa, patterns that differ from those of the Pacific. On the Atlantic coast of Canada, \citet{JohnsonMann1988} showed that \textit{Laminaria longicruris} has several patterns of adaptation that allow it to dominate in habitats of varying nutrient stress and disturbance levels, and \citet{SimmsDubois2001} developed satellite remote sensing techniques for mapping submerged kelp beds in this region. In glacially-impacted environments, \citet{Huovinen2020} showed that mapping of kelp in Patagonian fjords needs to account for special water optical properties affected by glacier runoff.

\textbf{Implications for detection systems:} These geographic variations suggest that: (1) detection algorithms developed using data from one region may not transfer well to other regions; (2) spectral signatures of kelp canopy change with species composition, water properties, and environmental conditions \citep{Turner2003); and (3) optimal detection heuristic for a given image tile depends on its geographic and environmental context. \citet{Wernberg2012} reviewed a decade of climate change experiments on marine organisms and found that small-scale manipulative experiments often fail to predict large-scale responses, reinforcing the need for monitoring

This geographic variability is the driving force behind the adaptive context-aware framework proposed in this thesis: Instead of searching for a single universal detection model, the Learning Automata approach is learning to choose the best heuristic for each environmental context, with the hypothesis that such adaptive selection will be better than any single fixed approach. \citet{Yong2005} demonstrated this principle for general image segmentation, showing that the learning-based algorithm selection approach using image features to predict optimal segmentation algorithms achieved 85% accuracy in choosing the best algorithm - a great precedent for adaptive heuristic selection in kelp detection.

\section{Monitoring Techniques in Kelp Forests}
\label{sec:lit-monitoring}

\subsection{Traditional Survey Methods}
\label{subsec:traditional-surveys}

Traditional kelp monitoring is based on direct observation by methods including:

\textbf{Shoreline surveys:} Walking or kayaking along shorelines at low tide to map visible kelp beds. While offering high spatial resolution and species identification, these methods are labor intensive, limited by access and able only to cover small portions of extensive coastlines.

\textbf{SCUBA transects:} Underwater surveys to document kelp density, size structure, and associated fauna along fixed transects. These provide the best ecological information but are very limited in spatial coverage and require specialized personnel.

\textbf{Aerial photography:} Fixed-wing aircrafts or helicopters taking oblique or vertical photographs. The ShoreZone project has gathered large amounts of oblique shoreline imagery for BC, which is a great historical baseline \citep{Starko2024}. However, aerial surveys are costly, depend on weather conditions, and are only carried out every 10--15 years.

\subsection{Remote Sensing Methods}
\label{subsec:remote-sensing}

Satellite remote sensing provides the spatial coverage required for coastline-scale monitoring, with a number of platforms providing relevant capabilities \citep{Bennion2019, Cavanaugh2021}:

\textbf{Landsat (30m resolution):} Longest continuous record of Earth observation, archives back to 1970s. \citet{Cavanaugh2010} Scaling of giant kelp field measurements to regional scales using Landsat. \citet{Cavanaugh2011} Environmental controls of kelp biomass through 25 years of Landsat observations, Santa Barbara Channel. \citet{MoraSoto2024} Long-term sentinel site analysis using Landsat at Ella Beach, BC over 50 years. \citet{Bell2020

\textbf{Sentinel-2 (10m resolution):} The European Space Agency's optical sensor offers improved spatial resolution, increased spectral bands (including red-edge bands sensitive to vegetation), and 5-day revisit time using the twin-satellite constellation. \citet{Gendall2023} developed a multi-satellite mapping framework incorporating Sentinel-2 for floating kelp canopy detection. \citet{MoraSoto2020} created a high-resolution global map of giant kelp forests using Sentinel-2, providing algorithm thresholds that can be applied across hemispheres. \citet{Timmer

\textbf{High-resolution commercial sensors:} WorldView-2/3 (1.2--2.6m) and CubeSat constellations such as PlanetScope (3m) provide fine spatial resolution. \citet{Schroeder2020} used WorldView imagery for detailed kelp mapping in the Cowichan Bay area with an overall accuracy of 86.9%. \citet{CavanaughKC2023} demonstrated PlanetScope for detecting fine scale kelp refugia that are missed by coarser resolution sensors.

\textbf{Unoccupied Aerial Vehicles (UAVs):} UAVs provide sub-meter resolution for local-scale monitoring and restoration assessment. \citet{Saccomanno2023} developed methods for mapping emergent kelp canopy after ecological regime shifts, demonstrating the complementary role of UAVs in conjunction with satellite data. \citet{CavanaughUAV2021} developed an automated method for mapping giant kelp canopy dynamics from UAV imagery, achieving 93% accuracy with multispectral sensors and quantifying the effects of tides and currents on visible kelp canopy.

\subsection{Classification Indexes and Methods}
\label{subsec:classification-methods}

Several spectral indices have been found to be effective in kelp detection:

\textbf{NDVI (Normalized Difference Vegetation Index):} Standard vegetation index with red and near-infrared bands. Effective for separating kelp and open water but can be confused by kelp and other floating vegetation or surface algae.

\textbf{GNDVI (Green Normalized Difference Vegetation Index):} Replaces red with green, making it more sensitive to chlorophyll content. \citet{Schroeder2020} found GNDVI complementary to NDVI for kelp classification.

\textbf{FAI (Floating Algae Index):} Developed for floating vegetation, FAI uses the red-edge spectral region where submergent and floating vegetation differ \citep{Gendall2023}.

\textbf{NDWI (Normalized Difference Water Index):} Useful for separating water from other surfaces but usually used as a mask rather than for direct kelp detection.

\subsection{Machine Learning to Detect Kelp}
\label{subsec:ml-kelp}

Recent developments in machine learning have made more complex methods of kelp detection possible \citep{Ma2019}:

\textbf{Random Forest and other ensemble methods:} Using several spectral features via decision tree ensembles has proven to be very effective for kelp classification. \citet{Ganaie2022} is a great review of ensemble deep learning methods. \citet{Savargiv2021} used learning automata integration with Random Forest for better classifier selection. \citet{TonionPirotti2022} achieved >98% overall accuracy using Random Forest for seaweed detection on the Irish coast, proving the potential of ML-based monitoring as long as sufficient training data is available.

\textbf{Convolutional Neural Networks:} Deep learning approaches, especially U-Net architectures for semantic segmentation, have shown state-of-the-art performance in kelp detection given sufficient training data \citep{Ma2019, Bai2023}. \citet{Marquez2022} demonstrated Mask R-CNN for giant kelp forest mapping from Landsat imagery, achieving Jaccard indices of 0.87 and enabling reconstruction of 32-year time series with reduced human effort. \citet{Mahmood2020} developed hierarchical classification using deep residual features for kel Most recently, \citet{Nasios2025} showed that the combination of Vision Transformers and ConvNeXt models and crowdsourced labels results in high kelp detection accuracy from Landsat imagery, identifying about three out of four kelp canopy pixels.

\textbf{Reinforcement Learning:} Deep reinforcement learning approaches are emerging for conservation decision-making \citep{Lapeyrolerie2022} which offers the potential for adaptive monitoring systems that can learn optimal strategies through interaction with the environment. \citet{Lindkvist2017} demonstrated that computational adaptive management using reinforcement learning can find optimal strategies for sustainable resource management during environmental change, with results showing that strategies optimized for declining growth rates are robust to fluctuating or increasing growth.

\textbf{Limitations:} These methods need a lot of labeled training data and may not generalize well to environmental conditions not included in training. The transfer learning challenge (adapting a model trained in one region/time period to new conditions) is an active research area. \citet{BeasLuna2020} showed that kelp forest responses to climate are heterogeneous across space, thus the need for adaptive approaches that consider regional heterogeneity.

\section{Learning Automata Theory}
\label{sec:lit-la}

\subsection{Historical Development and Foundations}
\label{subsec:la-foundations}

Learning Automata (LA) started in the Soviet Union in the 1960s with the groundbreaking work of Tsetlin \citep{Tsetlin1961} who proposed computational adaptive schemes for learning optimal actions in stochastic environments. The field grew out of the intersection of the theory of automata, stochastic processes, and behavioral psychology (especially the theories of conditioning and associative learning formalized computationally by \citet{BushMosteller1955}. LA share conceptual interfaces with reinforcement learning, multi-agent systems and control theory, but provide unique theoretical guarantees of particular importance to decision-making under uncertainty \citep{Narendra1989, ThathacharSastry2002, Bisong2018}.

The LA model works in a feedback loop between the automaton (decision-maker) and an unknown environment. This formulation is especially suitable for situations where little or no information is available \textit{a priori} about environmental response characteristics - a situation that closely resembles kelp monitoring, where detection algorithm performance varies in unpredictable ways from one environmental context to another.